1) What is a fast-forward merge?

A fast-forward merge happens when the target branch has no new commits since the feature branch was created, so Git simply moves the pointer forward without creating a merge commit.

👉 In short: linear history, no merge commit needed

Example:

main:    A --- B
feature:       \--- C --- D

After merge:

main:    A --- B --- C --- D
2) When does Git create a merge commit instead?

Git creates a merge commit when both branches have diverged, meaning each branch has new commits that the other doesn’t have.

👉 In short: non-linear history → Git needs a merge commit to combine histories

Example:

main:    A --- B --- E
               \
feature:        C --- D

After merge:

main:    A --- B --- E ------- M
               \             /
                C --------- D

Here, M is the merge commit.

3) What is a merge conflict?

A merge conflict occurs when Git cannot automatically merge changes because the same part of a file was modified differently in both branches.

👉 In short: Git doesn’t know which change to keep


